          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width=100% border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
<tr><td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_01.gif" width=6 height=6></td><td width=100% background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_02.gif"></td>
<td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_03.gif" width=6 height=6></td></tr>
<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> LotR Tournament Metagame.<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.29)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11358'>Robert "mackdi" McCaughtry</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11358&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> June 17, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> I want to begin this article by stating that my articles are observations and are not really meant for the &quot;pro&quot; LotR player. By pro I mean a person that goes to all the big LotR events like the origins and other cons, knows what every card does, and can tell which cards in new sets will be good by looking at the spoiler. The audience I will usually write for are the people that play in small towns, don&#39;t know every cards text by heart, etc.<br>
<br>
I also would like to introduce myself a little bit. My name is Robert McCaughtry. I am 21. I grew up in the metro area of St. Paul/Minneapolis Minnesota. I now live in Manhattan, Kansas. I am in classes at Kansas State University for computer science. LotR was introduced to me by a friend that is just nuts about LotR. My wife heard about it and decided to make LotR an activity we can share together. Until LotR came out I was all about Magic:the gathering. Due to recent events of shifting formats I decided to pay less attention to Magic and more to LotR.<br>
<br>
On to the real topic for this article.<br>
<br>
If you have read LotR tournament reports lately you will notice that most big tournament participants are using super fellowship combined with Uruk-hai or Moria shadow. Nazgul is still around but not in the numbers I was expecting. Sauron is almost non exsistant because the super fellowship have so many cards that just shut down the Sauron culture. <br>
<br>
So what is the super fellowship you may ask?<br>
a super fellowship means using around six to nine companions with their weapons and the best events you can have. Most super fellowship&#39;s use Arwen Daughter of Elrond, Legolas Greenleaf, Aragorn Either version, Boromir Lord of Gondor, Sam Son of Hamfast, and Gandalf Friend of the Shirefolk. Some even use Gimli and/or Merry. These decks have an answer for everything your shadow can throw at them. They just have to be able to draw into them. If your playing Uruks they have armor and a rangers versatily. If you use orcs of any kind you will find it hard to overwelm because of the high amount of companions to get in the way. If you use Nazgul, a rangers versatility becomes really good for them as does Arwen. <br>
<br>
So how do you beat the super fellowship? Kill companions quickly and by doing so you make it harder for them to cycle their hand. That is no easy task but it can be done.<br>
<br>
There are some cards that will help stop the fellowship from just running your shadow over. The few that I can think of as I am writing this are:<br>
<br>
Greed which spots six companions and lets you use two twilight to wound a companions except the ring bearer during the manuever phase.<br>
<br>
The Number Must Be Few which spots seven companions and makes the turn limit -1.<br>
<br>
Saurons Defenses which spots three companions in the dead pile the turn limit is -1.<br>
<br>
By looks Sauron orcs have the best chance at stopping the super fellowship if you can stop or survive a Sleep, Caradhras. Whether you just get lucky and they don&#39;t draw it or you find a way to kill Gandalf before they can use Sleep. Saurons Defenses can be used in the direct damage style of Sauron. where you use Orc Bowmen, Under the Watching Eye, Hate, various trackers and all the orcs that exert to wound like Orc Scouting Band. Between all that damage dealing you should be able to get three companions dead before too long. I seem to never have good luck with direct damage Sauron. I always seem to draw Orc Bowmen or Under the Watching Eye but not like two or three of each in play until its too late. The Number Must Be Few could be good but the super fellowship could work around that by not having more then six out at a time.<br>
<br>
For the Uruks you can use a few Greed. I like the idea of Greed. With all the damage +1 Uruks and one use of Greed a lot of companions end up dead. The only downside to greed is it can be played around as usually the super fellowship stays keeps their companions count down to four as much as possible to keep Savagery to Match Their Numbers from becoming abusive. Also you will usually kill one or two companions and then they will never reach six companions again because they only run seven or eight companions. So Greed which can work has to be used on Gandalf or Aragorn to really do much. <br>
<br>
*****Sidenote*****<br>
So many people are playing Uruk-Hai shadow in the big tournaments is not even funny. I knew Uruks would be good because they are stable and can win skirmishes but I never imagined they would be running the tournament scene by themselves. It seems running all the armors in the world won&#39;t stop the Uruks right now. I believe it was in a Washington TOC that the guy reporting was using Uruks and everyone he played against used Uruks too. Even my Kansas TOC was Uruk heavy. If my wife didn&#39;t have dibs on our Uruks I would be playing them. I am putting out a challenge to you readers. Find a good way to crush the Uruks! Lets change the metagame for the better. I suppose you can attribute the current metagame due to only two sets being released and that hopefully Realm of the Elf Lords and Two Towers can correct for this super fellowship/Uruk madness.<br>
<br>
In short if you want to play in big tournaments your deck better be able to stand up to super fellowship/uruk decks. I think one that shows promise ,whether it can do it or not remains to be seen, is a small fellowship that uses a great amount of utility that can choke the shadow and kill or survive what does show up and Sauron direct damage shadow.<br>
<br>
